<p>Welcome to this year's 27th issue of DWN, the weekly newsletter for the
Debian community.  Jordi Mallach <a
href="http://oskuro.net/blog/freesoftware/cupsys-transition-done-2004-07-12-09-26">\
reported</a> that the transition of GNOME 2.6 into testing is nearly sorted
out.  Steve McIntyre <a
href="http://blog.einval.com/2004/07/09#md5-considered-harmful">explained</a>
that the CD/DVD creation process in debian-cd is very slow because large
amounts of data are read and written, and because that data is checked with
checksums several times.</p>

<p><strong>Debian Software used at Google.</strong> Marc Merlin of <a
href="http://www.google.com/">Google</a> fame reported in an <a
href="http://www.computerworld.com.au/index.php/id;1306281842;fp;16;fpid;0">\
interview</a> that Debian is the most comprehensive software library available
for GNU/Linux.  He uses <code>apt-get</code> and an overall
<code>getupdates</code> mechanism to keep the huge farm of servers in
sync.  The tool itself is distribution- and even Unix-agnostic, though.</p>

<p><strong>New Debian based Distribution.</strong> <a
href="http://www.nmxs.com/">New Mexico Software, Inc.</a> (NMXS) <a
href="http://biz.yahoo.com/prnews/040708/flth017_1.html">announced</a> that it
will release the new Santa Fe desktop environment which is Desktop-oriented
and based on Debian GNU/Linux on August 3rd this year.  Dick Govatski, CEO of
NMXS is proud about its ease of use: "Users won't have to be a Linux guru to
easily use the system."  They apparently have spent special effort on
the installer and its hardware detection.</p>

<p><strong>Lacking commercial Support for Debian?</strong> An <a
href="http://www.itnews.com.au/storycontent.asp?ID=6&amp;Art_ID=20436">article</a>
about GNU/Linux
adoption in organisations, shows that Debian may need to advertise its
<a href="$(HOME)/consultants/">commercial support</a> pages more prominently:
"All the contracting
houses said if you want Red Hat, it's not a problem, but Debian was
harder" said Mike Kennedy, CIO for Australia's New South Wales Office
of State Revenue who have switched their GNU/Linux servers from Debian to
Red Hat.</p>

<p><strong>Debian Control Center IRC Meeting.</strong>  David Moreno Garza <a
href="http://lists.debian.org/debian-desktop/2004/07/msg00000.html">\
announced</a> an IRC meeting on July 18th at 16:00 GMT, at #debian-desktop
on irc.debian.org.  The main <a
href="http://lists.debian.org/debian-desktop/2004/05/msg00025.html">idea</a>
is to bring users the capacity to configure their entire system.  With
portability in mind it is planned to provide a graphical interface, a
web-based one and a command-line driven interface.</p>

<p><strong>Move Exim 4 to BerkelyDB 4.2?</strong> Andreas Metzler <a
href="http://lists.debian.org/debian-release/2004/07/msg00015.html">\
wondered</a> if it would be acceptable to switch <a
href="http://packages.debian.org/exim4">Exim 4</a> to a newer version of
BerkelyDB, namely <a href="http://packages.debian.org/libdb4.2">\
libdb4.2</a>.  Since the release of sarge is planned for the near future, such
a change may have the potential to delay the release but shouldn't.</p>

<p><strong>Watching new Upstream Versions.</strong> Stefano Fabri <a
href="http://lists.debian.org/debian-devel/2004/debian-devel-200404/msg06580.html">\
announced</a> <a href="http://dehs.alioth.debian.org/">Debian Watch Health
Status</a>, a service for Debian developers to monitor upstream package
versions.  He <a
href="http://lists.debian.org/debian-devel/2004/05/msg00213.html">\
complained</a> that only very few packages contain proper <code>watch</code>
files to utilise this.  Blars Blarson <a
href="http://lists.debian.org/debian-devel/2004/05/msg00268.html">assumed</a>
that many maintainers don't find them useful.</p>

<p><strong>Bug Squashing Party.</strong> Frank Lichtenheld <a
href="http://lists.debian.org/debian-devel-announce/2004/07/msg00009.html">\
announced</a> the next Debian bug squashing party on July 16th to 18th.  As
usual it will be coordinated through #debian-bugs on freenode
(i.e. irc.debian.org) where you will find pointers to all the useful
websites, too.  The overall goal is to get the <a
href="http://bugs.qa.debian.org/cgi-bin/base.cgi">base system</a> and <a
href="http://bugs.qa.debian.org/cgi-bin/standard.cgi">standard packages</a> in
a releasable state.</p>

<p><strong>Discouraged Use of -rpath.</strong> Martin F. Krafft <a
href="http://lists.debian.org/debian-devel/2004/06/msg00734.html">wondered</a>
why the <a href="http://wiki.debian.org/RpathIssue">rpath issue</a>
is not documented in the <a href="$(HOME)/doc/debian-policy/">policy
manual</a>.  Florian Ernst <a
href="http://lists.debian.org/debian-devel/2004/06/msg00740.html">contributed</a>
another <a href="http://lists.debian.org/debian-devel/2002/07/msg01729.html">\
thread</a> and a <a
href="http://lists.debian.org/debian-devel/2002/07/msg02030.html">summary</a>
by Richard Atterer.  Goswin Brederlow <a
href="http://lists.debian.org/debian-devel/2004/06/msg00755.html">added</a>
that anything that uses <code>-rpath</code> will break after the release of
sarge if multiarch support is introduced.</p>

<p><strong>Python Modules and Versions.</strong> Fabio Tranchitella <a
href="http://lists.debian.org/debian-devel/2004/06/msg00819.html">\
noticed</a> that a lot of Python modules are not versioned and are available
only for particular versions of Python.  Matt Zimmerman <a
href="http://lists.debian.org/debian-devel/2004/06/msg00902.html">\
wondered</a> why those modules couldn't be byte-compiled after the
installation for each installed version of Python.  Andreas Barth <a
href="http://lists.debian.org/debian-devel/2004/06/msg00927.html">added</a>
that byte-compilation is not even required.</p>

